{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17590554","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17590554"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T09:49:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15201"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15201","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15201"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.04,0.09,0.04,0.74]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7892"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68516"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7892"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15201"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53973"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4937"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8115"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19232"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19233"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68516"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA pathologist is examining a bladder biopsy specimen under microscopic examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following histological features is most characteristic of urothelial carcinoma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Squamous pearls with keratin formation","Spindle cells in fascicular pattern","Glandular formation with mucin production","Small round blue cells in sheets","Nuclear pleomorphism with disrupted umbrella cell layer"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EUrothelial carcinoma (also known as transitional cell carcinoma) characteristically shows \u003Cstrong\u003Enuclear pleomorphism with disrupted umbrella cell layer\u003C/strong\u003E. The umbrella cells are the superficial cells of normal urothelium that become disorganised in cancer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect patterns help distinguish other tumour types:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESquamous pearls with keratin formation\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of squamous cell carcinoma\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpindle cells in fascicular pattern\u003C/strong\u003E suggest sarcomatoid differentiation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlandular formation with mucin production\u003C/strong\u003E is seen in adenocarcinoma\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall round blue cells in sheets\u003C/strong\u003E are typical of small cell carcinoma\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrothelial carcinoma is the most common type of bladder cancer, accounting for about 90% of cases. The histological features reflect the origin of the tumour from the transitional epithelium lining the urinary tract.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Urothelial carcinoma shows characteristic nuclear pleomorphism and disrupted umbrella cells on histology","Transitional cell carcinoma is the most common type of bladder cancer, accounting for 90% of cases","Different histological patterns help distinguish between types of bladder cancer including squamous cell, adenocarcinoma, and small cell variants"],"references":["Tanaka MF, Sonpavde G. Diagnosis and management of urothelial carcinoma of the bladder. Postgrad Med. 2011 May;123(3):43-55. doi: 10.3810/pgm.2011.05.2283. PMID: 21566415.","Leslie SW, Soon-Sutton TL, Aeddula NR. Bladder Cancer. 2024 Aug 15. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30725608.","Ogbue O, Haddad A, Almassi N, Lapinski J, Daw H. Overview of histologic variants of urothelial carcinoma: current trends and narrative review on treatment outcomes. Transl Androl Urol. 2022 Jun;11(6):877-901. doi: 10.21037/tau-22-43. PMID: 35812199; PMCID: PMC9262735.","Takahara T, Murase Y, Tsuzuki T. Urothelial carcinoma: variant histology, molecular subtyping, and immunophenotyping significant for treatment outcomes. Pathology. 2021 Jan;53(1):56-66. doi: 10.1016/j.pathol.2020.09.004. Epub 2020 Oct 16. PMID: 33070956."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53973"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15201"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53973","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53973"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T19:52:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T19:53:30+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7892"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68516"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Le